        "creation_date": 1384944050,
        "answer_count": 2,
        "title": "To open Project Properties WIndow (Java Build Path) automatically using code",
        "body": "<p>I am developing an Eclipse plugin which would create a new Java project and few classes inside it.\nOnce the plugin wizard closes (after I click finish in the final page), i need the Project Properties window of this particular project to be opened automatically.<\/p>\n\n<p>I must achieve that through code, any examples please?<\/p>\n",
        "question_id": 20093637,
        "tags": [
            "java",
            "eclipse-plugin",
            "buildpath"
        ],
        "score": 2,
        "accepted_answer_id": 20191992,
        "is_answered": true,
        "view_count": 1256
    },
    "question_comments": [],
    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/4iPV5.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 3159259,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2670892,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2670892/greg-449",
                "reputation": 111562,
                "display_name": "greg-449"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 3,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1385021014,
            "creation_date": 1384948271,
            "body": "<p>Use <code>org.eclipse.ui.dialogs.PreferencesUtil<\/code><\/p>\n\n<pre><code>PreferencesUtil.createPropertyDialogOn(shell, element, null, null, null).open();\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>will display the full <code>Properties<\/code> dialog. The parameters allow you to choose the initial page and filter the pages shown.<\/p>\n\n<p>The <code>element<\/code> parameter would be the <code>IProject<\/code> for the project.<\/p>\n\n<p>You can find existing property page ids using the Eclipse <code>Search<\/code> dialog. Select the <code>Plug-in Search<\/code> tab and enter the property page extension point id <code>org.eclipse.ui.propertyPages<\/code> in the <code>Search string<\/code>. Set <code>Search For<\/code> to <code>Extension Point<\/code>, set <code>Limit To<\/code> to <code>References<\/code> and <code>Scope<\/code> to <code>Workspace<\/code>. \n<img src=\"https://i.sstatic.net/vw6TZ.png\" alt=\"Search dialog\"><\/p>\n\n<p>Perform the search to get the plug-ins which use this extension point. Opening a search result will open the plugin.xml for the plugin at the extension point.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 20095169,
            "question_id": 20093637,
            "last_edit_date": 1385021014
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/8Fl85.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 2980560,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2530599,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2530599/uma",
                "reputation": 327,
                "display_name": "uma",
                "accept_rate": 70
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 3,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1385379037,
            "creation_date": 1385379037,
            "body": "<p>I got the final answer. This is how it goes:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Shell shell = PlatformUI.getWorkbench().getActiveWorkbenchWindow().getShell();\nMessageDialog.openInformation(shell, \"Project Proeperties\", \"Properties window will open next\");\n\nString propertyPageId = \"org.eclipse.jdt.ui.propertyPages.BuildPathsPropertyPage\";\nPreferenceDialog dialog = PreferencesUtil.createPropertyDialogOn(shell, iProject, propertyPageId, null, null);\n    dialog.open();\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 20191992,
            "question_id": 20093637
        }
    ],
